<section class="page-hero">
  <h1>Before You Adopt</h1>
  <p>Rabbits make wonderful companions — but they're not the low-maintenance pet many people expect. Here's what you need to know.</p>
</section>

<div class="prose">
  <h2>Is a Rabbit Right for You?</h2>
  <p>Rabbits are intelligent, affectionate, and full of personality. They can also live <strong>10 to 12 years</strong>, require specialized veterinary care, and need daily attention and space to thrive. Adopting a rabbit is a long-term commitment — not unlike adopting a cat or dog.</p>
  <p>Before you fall in love with a fluffy face, honestly consider whether your lifestyle, budget, and living situation can support a rabbit for the next decade.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <h3>The Quick Checklist</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Time:</strong> 10+ year commitment with daily interaction needed</li>
      <li><strong>Space:</strong> Large indoor enclosure plus daily exercise space</li>
      <li><strong>Cost:</strong> $500–$1,000+ per year (food, hay, litter, vet care)</li>
      <li><strong>Vet care:</strong> Exotic/rabbit-savvy veterinarian required — not all vets treat rabbits</li>
      <li><strong>Patience:</strong> Rabbits are prey animals; trust is earned slowly</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>What Rabbits Need</h2>

  <h3>Indoor Housing</h3>
  <p>Rabbits should live indoors. Outdoor hutches expose rabbits to predators, extreme temperatures, parasites, and isolation. Indoor rabbits live longer, healthier lives and bond more closely with their families.</p>
  <p>At minimum, a rabbit needs an enclosure large enough to take three full hops in any direction — plus several hours of supervised free-roaming time daily. Many rabbit owners choose to "bunny-proof" a room or area of their home rather than rely on a cage.</p>

  <h3>Diet</h3>
  <p>A healthy rabbit diet is built on <strong>unlimited timothy hay</strong> (or other grass hay), which should make up about 80% of their food. This is supplemented with fresh leafy greens daily, a small portion of quality pellets, and unlimited fresh water.</p>
  <p>Sugary treats, seeds, and many commercially marketed "rabbit treats" are harmful and should be avoided. Carrots, despite the stereotype, are high in sugar and should be offered sparingly.</p>

  <h3>Veterinary Care</h3>
  <p>Rabbits are classified as <strong>exotic animals</strong>, which means you'll need a vet who specializes in rabbit medicine. Regular checkups, spay/neuter surgery, dental monitoring, and emergency care all require a rabbit-savvy veterinarian.</p>
  <p>Spaying or neutering is strongly recommended — it prevents reproductive cancers (very common in unaltered female rabbits), reduces hormonal behavior, and is a prerequisite for adoption from most rescues.</p>

  <h3>Enrichment &amp; Companionship</h3>
  <p>Rabbits are social animals who need mental stimulation. Toys, tunnels, digging boxes, and foraging activities help prevent boredom and destructive behavior. Many rabbits also benefit from having a bonded rabbit companion, though introductions must be done carefully.</p>

  <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>"Rabbits are starter pets for kids."</strong> Rabbits are fragile, easily stressed by loud noises and rough handling, and require a level of care that most young children can't provide independently. They're better suited as a family pet with adult primary caregivers.</li>
    <li><strong>"Rabbits are low-maintenance."</strong> Between daily hay and litter changes, fresh greens, exercise time, grooming, and regular vet visits, rabbits require consistent daily care.</li>
    <li><strong>"Rabbits can live in a cage."</strong> A cage alone is not sufficient. Rabbits need significant daily exercise and exploration time outside of any enclosure.</li>
    <li><strong>"Easter bunnies make great gifts."</strong> Impulse rabbit purchases around Easter lead to a surge in abandoned rabbits every spring. A rabbit is a decade-long commitment, not a seasonal novelty.</li>
    <li><strong>"Rabbits can live outside."</strong> Outdoor rabbits face shortened lifespans due to predation, weather exposure, disease, and lack of socialization. All major rabbit welfare organizations recommend indoor housing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Case for Adoption</h2>
  <p>Florida's rabbit rescues are full of rabbits who were surrendered, abandoned, or rescued from unsafe situations. Many are already spayed/neutered, socialized, and evaluated for temperament — which means adopting from a rescue gives you a head start on a great relationship.</p>
  <p>Adoption also supports the rescue organizations that do this work, and it frees up space for the next rabbit who needs help.</p>

